id: ID variable that is different for each sample and constant for identical/dependent/overlapping samples
rowid: combines id and row-number - needed for lookup
cos:
Minimum variables coded for cos collaboration (regardless of validation)?
1 = yes
0 = no
NA = no
validated:
Has this entry been validated? [to be filled out by core-team only]

NA = no
0 = no

1 = yes and everything is correct (corresponds to what is reported in the source)
2 = yes and errors were highlighted, corrected, and commented in notes_validation
3 = yes, errors have not yet been corrected

4 = [for individual submissions only] necessary values are present / data is sufficient for effect sizes calculation
5 = [for individual submissions only] some values are missing
6 = [for individual submissions only] data is complete and has been validated with respect to its sources (e.g., papers, datasets)
7 = [for batch submissions only] data corresponds to a secondary source but has not been validated with respect to primary sources
validated_person: Who has checked the entry? [to be filled out by core-team only]
source: source of the entry for historic purposes; if you add something this should be "individual submissions"
discipline: Which scientific discipline does the finding come from or where has it been published?
effect:
What is the phenomenon or "effect" called? (e.g., "heat priming")

leave empty if there is no association with a family of phenomena
tags: tags to increase findability of the entry, separated by commas
description: Description of the effect/phenomenon under investigation (e.g., x is associated with y, x leads to y), possibly a part of the original publication's title (abstract claim)
claim_text_orig: The authors’ conclusion or interpretation of the statistical evidence
claim_statistics_orig: The statistical test results that support a key finding from the study
claim_statistics_orig_page: Page number of the statistical test results that support a key finding from the study
claim_text_orig_page: Page number of the authors’ conclusion or interpretation of the statistical evidence
notes: Notes for data entry (e.g., something is missing, behind a paywall, there are inconsistencies, you are uncertain about something)
contributors:
For individual submissions: name of the person who submitted the effect to ReD
For FORRT-entries: Name of the person who completed the entry
For all others: Names of the contributors of the study
notes_validation: Notes regarding the test
es_original: Original effect size converted to r [please rather enter the unconverted effect size into the variable "es_orig_value"]
es_replication: Replication effect size converted to r [please rather enter the unconverted effect size into the variable "es_orig_value"]
n_original: Original study's sample size [use sample size that was used for the critical test, i.e., after exclusion criteria have been applied]
n_replication: Replication study's sample size [use sample size that was used for the critical test, i.e., after exclusion criteria have been applied]
ref_original:
Reference of the original study + Study number
(APA7 formatting + Study number)
doi_original: DOI for the reference of the original study [without "http" or "dx.doi.org"]
refonly_original: Reference of the original study [red ones need to be reformatted to APA]
study_original: Study number of the original study (e.g., 1, 1a, A)
ref_replication: Reference (APA7 formatting) of the replication study + Study number
doi_replication: DOI for the reference of the replication study [without "http" or "dx.doi.org"]
refonly_replication: Reference of the replication study
study_replication: Study number of the replication study (e.g., 1, 1a, A)
es_orig: original effect size as formatted in the source materials [included for batch submissions and validation purposes, please leave this empty if you submit something]
es_rep: replication effect size as formatted in the source materials [included for batch submissions and validation purposes, please leave this empty if you submit something]
es_orig_estype: original effect size type (e.g., d, r, r², etasq)
pval_value_o: The reported p-value associated with the original finding
pval_type_o:
The p-value format of the original finding, taking the values of less-than, equal to, or greater than
equal to: e
less than: l
greater than: g
less equal: le
greater equal: ge

for example "p < .05" should be coded as "l"
pval_tails_o:
How many tails associated with the p-value, taking on values of one, two, or unknown

one: 1
two: 2
unknown / not specified: NA
missing: not coded
pval_value_r: The reported p-value associated with the replication finding
pval_type_r:
The p-value format of the replication finding, taking the values of less-than, equal to, or greater than

equal to: e
less than: l
greater than: g
less equal: le
greater equal: ge

for example "p < .05" should be coded as "l"
pval_tails_r:
How many tails associated with the p-value, taking on values of one, two, or unknown

one: 1
two: 2
unknown: NA
missing: not coded
es_orig_RRR: obsolete variable, included for historic reasons
es_orig_RRR_estype: obsolete variable, included for historic reasons
es_rep_RRR: obsolete variable, included for historic reasons
es_rep_RRR_estype: obsolete variable, included for historic reasons
osf_link: Link to the OSF project or to another repository (e.g., researchbox) that includes materials and data for the replication study
outcome: outcome of the replication study with respect to direction and difference between original and replication effect; automatically computed based on provided test statistics, please leave empty
published_rep:
Has the replication study been published?
0 = no
1 = as pre-print
2 = as peer-reviewed journal article
3 = as other (thesis, data set, ...)
id_sample: unique ID per sample (if 2 effects originate from one sample, then enter the same values in each case), also code two cases as the same id_sample if their samples overlap more than ~80%
same_design:
Was the same design used in the replication study (e.g., within-subjects design, number of factors and factor levels, nesting, ...)
0 = no, 1 = yes
nesting: Were all observations independent, nested, matched, clustered, ...?
same_test:
Was the same statistical test used in the replication study (e.g., t-test, ANOVA, ...)?
0 = no, 1 = yes
original_authors:
Was any of the original study's authors involved in the replication study?
0 = no, 1 = yes
study_orig: Number / sample / page of the original study
study_rep: Number / sample / page of the replication study
teststatistic_orig: full test statistic for respective finding
teststatistic_rep: full test statistic for respective finding
p_es_orig: page number of the original effect size
p_es_rep: page number of the replication effect size
p_n_orig: page number of the original sample size
p_n_rep: page number of the replication sample size
p_p_orig: page number of the original p-value
p_p_rep: page number of the replication p-value
result: success, informative failure to replicate, practical failure to replicate, inconclusive [taken from the respective reports and if not reported automatically computed; success = both effects are significant in the same direction]
preregistration: link to the preregistration of the replication study
closeness_instructions:
Closeness between original study and replication study with regards to instructions.
See also Replication Recipe; 1 = exact, 2 = close, 3 = different, or 4 = does not apply, 5 = unknown.
closeness_measures:
Closeness between original study and replication study with regards to measures.
See also Replication Recipe; 1 = exact, 2 = close, 3 = different, or 4 = does not apply, 5 = unknown.
closeness_stimuli:
Closeness between original study and replication study with regards to stimuli.
See also Replication Recipe; 1 = exact, 2 = close, 3 = different, or 4 = does not apply, 5 = unknown.
closeness_procedure:
Closeness between original study and replication study with regards to procedure.
See also Replication Recipe; 1 = exact, 2 = close, 3 = different, or 4 = does not apply, 5 = unknown.
closeness_location:
Closeness between original study and replication study with regards to location where the study was conducted (e.g., city-country-continent, lab vs. field).
See also Replication Recipe; 1 = exact, 2 = close, 3 = different, or 4 = does not apply, 5 = unknown.
closeness_renumeration:
Closeness between original study and replication study with regards to remuneration (e.g., payment, feedback on personal data such as IQ values, course credit).
See also Replication Recipe; 1 = exact, 2 = close, 3 = different, or 4 = does not apply, 5 = unknown.
closeness_participants:
Closeness between original study and replication study with regards to participants (e.g., convenience sample, student sample, clickworkers).
See also Replication Recipe; 1 = exact, 2 = close, 3 = different, or 4 = does not apply, 5 = unknown.
closeness_exclusions:
Closeness between original study and replication study with regards to exclusions.
See also Replication Recipe; 1 = exact, 2 = close, 3 = different, or 4 = does not apply, 5 = unknown.
closeness_language:
Closeness between original study and replication study with regards to language.
See also Replication Recipe; 1 = exact, 2 = close, 3 = different, or 4 = does not apply, 5 = unknown.
closeness_nationality:
Closeness between original study and replication study with regards to nationality.
See also Replication Recipe; 1 = exact, 2 = close, 3 = different, or 4 = does not apply, 5 = unknown.
differences: Specification of all differences between the original study and the replication written in bullet points or plain text.
vi_orig: variances of original effects, automatically computed
vi_rep: variances of replication effects, automatically computed
ci.lower_original: lower confidence interval for the standardized effect size (replication effect), automatically computed
ci.upper_original: upper confidence interval for the standardized effect size (replication effect), automatically computed
ci.lower_replication: lower confidence interval for the standardized effect size (replication effect), automatically computed
ci.upper_replication: upper confidence interval for the standardized effect size (replication effect), automatically computed
significant_original: was the original effect significant? 1 = yes, 0 = no, automatically computed
significant_replication: was the replication effect significant? 1 = yes, 0 = no, automatically computed
power: Replication study power based on replication N and original effect size converted to r, automatically computed
orig_journal: Journal that published the original findings

id: ID-Variable zur eindeutigen Identifizierung von einzelnen Stichproben
validated:
Wurde dieser Eintrag validiert? 
1 = ja und alles korrekt [=übereinstimmend mit Quelle], "" = nein,
2 = ja und Fehler wurden markiert, korrigiert, und in notes_validation kommentiert)
3 = ja, Fehler wurde noch nicht korrigiert
validated_person: Wer hat den Eintrag geprüft (gerne nur Kürzel eintragen)?
tags: Stichwörter des Eintrages zur besseren Findbarkeit
notes: Notizen der Dateneingabe
contributors: Bei Einzeleinreichungen: Name der Person, die den Effekt bei ReD eingereicht hat
notes_validation: Notizen bezüglich der Prüfung
exclusion: Grund für den Ausschluss von der Studie
es_original: Originaleffektstärke in r konvertiert [lieber bei es_orig_value eintragen und nicht selbst konvertieren]
es_replication: Replikationseffektstärke in r konvertiert [lieber bei es_orig_value eintragen und nicht selbst konvertieren]
ref_original: Quellenangabe nach APA7 der Originalstudie
ref_replication: Quellenangabe nach APA7 der Replikationsstudie
study_replication: Studiennummer der Replikationsstudie
es_orig: Originaleffekt wie er von Dritten eingetragen wurde
es_rep: Replikationseffekt wie er von Dritten eingetragen wurde
osf_link: Link zum OSF Projekt oder zur Präregistrierung
published_rep:
Wurde die Replikationsstudie veröffentlicht?
0 = nein
1 = als pre-print
2 = als begutachteter Zeitschriftenartikel
3 = als sonstiges (Abschlussarbeit, Datensatz, …)
id_sample: einzigartige ID je Stichprobe (wenn aus einer Stichprobe 2 Effekte stammen, dann jeweils selbe Werte eintragen)
same_design: Wurde in der Replikationsstudie das gleiche Design verwendet (z. B. within-subjects design, Anzahl der Faktoren und Faktorstufen, Verschachtelung, ...)0 = nein, 1 = ja
same_test: Wurde in der Replikationsstudie derselbe statistische Test verwendet (z. B. t-Test, ANOVA, ...)? 0 = nein, 1 = ja
original_authors: War einer der Autor*innen an der ursprünglichen Studie an der Replikationsstudie beteiligt? 0 = nein, 1 = ja
p_es_orig: für neue Einträge [später erst relevant]
result: success, informative failure to replicate, practical failure to replicate, inconclusive
orig_journal: Zeitschrift, bei der die Originalstudie veröffentlicht wurde

description: Heat-Priming is associated with increased hostile perceptions
claim_text_orig: Pairwise comparisons showed that participants primed with hot temperature words (M = 7.85, SD = 1.24) rated Donald as more hostile than did participants primed with [...] cold temperature words (M = 6.79, SD = 1.86) [...] F(1, 69) = 5.02, p < .03, d = .67.
claim_statistics_orig: Pairwise comparisons showed that participants primed with hot temperature words (M = 7.85, SD = 1.24) rated Donald as more hostile than did participants primed with [...] cold temperature words (M = 6.79, SD = 1.86) [...] F(1, 69) = 5.02, p < .03, d = .67.
notes: there were two replications but the preregistration only referred to one (data here is from Study 1 in the lab); other effect sizes available

tags: Theory of Mind, implicit Theory of Mind, eye-tracking
description: Implicit Theory of Mind can be measured through anticipatory looking patterns measured through eye-tracking.
notes: Crucially, in the replication only the "FB1" condition was replicated, which is prone to alternative explanations, while the "FB2" condition, which exlcudes alternative explanations showed effects in the opposite direction to the original study.
ref_original: Southgate, V., Senju, A., & Csibra, G. (2007). Action anticipation through attribution of false belief by 2-year-olds. Psychological science, 18(7), 587-592.
refonly_original: Southgate, V., Senju, A., & Csibra, G. (2007). Action anticipation through attribution of false belief by 2-year-olds. Psychological science, 18(7), 587-592. https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1467-9280.2007.01944.x
ref_replication: Kulke, L., Von Duhn, B., Schneider, D., & Rakoczy, H. (2018). Is implicit theory of mind a real and robust phenomenon? results from a systematic replication study. Psychological Science, 29(6), 888–900.
refonly_replication: Kulke, L., Von Duhn, B., Schneider, D., & Rakoczy, H. (2018). Is implicit theory of mind a real and robust phenomenon? results from a systematic replication study. Psychological Science, 29(6), 888–900. https://doi.org/10.1177/0956797617747090
p_es_orig: Kulke, L., von Duhn, B., Schneider, D., & Rakoczy, H. (2018). Is implicit theory of mind a real and robust phenomenon? Results from a systematic replication study. Psychological science, 29(6), 888-900., p.893
differences:
The replication tested adults instead of the toddlers tested in the original study, as the original and later studies suggest that the effect is consistent across the life span. The replication included four different paradigms which were tested within participants, while the original only included one paradigm. The replication computed the same eye movement measures but used the Differential Looking Score (DLS) as suggested in a later study by the original authors (Senju et al., 2009); therefore, the used statistics differ. The replication tested German participants, instead of British participants. The authors of the original study provided the original stimuli for the replication. One author of a different original Theory of Mind paradigm is also a co-author on the replication. 
 Crucially, in the replication only the "FB1" condition was replicated, which is prone to alternative explanations, while the "FB2" condition, which exlcudes alternative explanations showed effects in the opposite direction to the original study.

tags: utilitarianism, alcohol, CNI Model, trolley dilemma, moral judgmenet
notes: We revisited the "drunk utilitarian" phenomena which was indicated by Duke and Begue in 2015. Our study replicated the results of Francis et al., 2019, and Arutyunova et al., 2017 but we proposed more strict methodolody and more measures to study utilitarianism. We show that there is no such phenomena as "drunk utilitarian", people are not more utilitarian when they are under the influence of the alcohol.

tags: social cognition, empathy, placebo, expectation,
ref_original: Rütgen, M., Seidel, E. M., Silani, G., Riečanský, I., Hummer, A., Windischberger, C., ... & Lamm, C. (2015). Placebo analgesia and its opioidergic regulation suggest that empathy for pain is grounded in self pain. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 112(41), E5638-E5646 (empathy for pain ratings)
refonly_original: Rütgen, M., Seidel, E. M., Silani, G., Riečanský, I., Hummer, A., Windischberger, C., ... & Lamm, C. (2015). Placebo analgesia and its opioidergic regulation suggest that empathy for pain is grounded in self pain. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 112(41), E5638-E5646. https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.1511269112
ref_replication: Hartmann, H., Forbes, P. A., Rütgen, M., & Lamm, C. (2022). Placebo analgesia reduces costly prosocial helping to lower another person’s pain. Psychological Science, 33(11), 1867-1881.(unpleasantness ratings)
refonly_replication: Hartmann, H., Forbes, P. A., Rütgen, M., & Lamm, C. (2022). Placebo analgesia reduces costly prosocial helping to lower another person’s pain. Psychological Science, 33(11), 1867-1881. https://doi.org/10.31234/osf.io/drfht
study_replication: unpleasentnass ratings
p_es_orig:
Original study: Supporting information, p. 1 (https://www.pnas.org/action/downloadSupplement?doi=10.1073%2Fpnas.1511269112&file=pnas.201511269SI.pdf)
 
 Replication study: Supplementary Material, p. 17 (bottom of https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/09567976221119727)
differences: Different point in time, slightly adjusted protocol because focus of the study was another task (prosocial behavior) while the focus of the original study was the empathy effect I am recording here, different experimenters and study doctors
orig_journal: Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America

tags: social value orientation (TDM); secure attachment (AAS); sample 1
description: prosocials have a higher level of secure attachment than individualists
notes: only 458 participants in the original paper and 1279 in sample 1 were included in the analysis because of unclassified participants by TDM; number of competitors was very low.
notes_validation: There are more effects in the original and the replication study which are not relevant to the main hypotheses. The preregistration link was incorrect; it was the OSF link for the OSF folder.
ref_original: Van Lange, P. A. M., De Bruin, E., Otten, W., & Joireman, J. A. (1997). Development of prosocial, individualistic, and competitive orientations: Theory and preliminary evidence. Journal of Personality and Social Psychology, 73(4), 733–746. https://doi.org/10.1037/0022-3514.73.4.733 Study 1
refonly_original: Van Lange, P. A. M., De Bruin, E., Otten, W., & Joireman, J. A. (1997). Development of prosocial, individualistic, and competitive orientations: Theory and preliminary evidence. Journal of Personality and Social Psychology, 73(4), 733–746. https://doi.org/10.1037/0022-3514.73.4.733
ref_replication: Liu, Y., Wang, B., & Van Lange, P. a. M. (2022). The development of social value orientation: Attachment styles, number of siblings, age, and a comparison of measures. European Journal of Personality, 37(4), 402–417.
refonly_replication: Liu, Y., Wang, B., & Van Lange, P. a. M. (2022). The development of social value orientation: Attachment styles, number of siblings, age, and a comparison of measures. European Journal of Personality, 37(4), 402–417. https://doi.org/10.1177/08902070221094216
differences: (1) the sample of the study is from the US and UK instead of the Netherlands, thus the language used in the studies is different;(2) some of the measures (e.g., SLM for SVO, AAS and ECR-R for attachment) are not the same as the original study, but we include the measures used in the original study as well; (3) the original Studies 1 and 3 were conducted in paper-and-pencil, while the current studies were conducted online; (4) the replication study has a larger sample size
orig_journal: Journal of Personality and Social Psychology

refonly_original: Granow, V. C., Reinecke, L., & Ziegele, M. (2018). Binge-Watching and Psychological Well-Being: Media Use Between Lack of Control and Perceived Autonomy. Communication Research Reports, 35(5), 392–401. https://doi.org/10.1080/08824096.2018.1525347
ref_replication: Erdmann, E., & Dienlin, T. (2022). Binge-watching, self-determination, and well-being: A partially successful direct replication and extension of Granow et al. (2018). Journal of Media Psychology, 1864-1105/a000334.
refonly_replication: Erdmann, E., & Dienlin, T. (2022). Binge-watching, self-determination, and well-being: A partially successful direct replication and extension of Granow et al. (2018). Journal of Media Psychology, 1864-1105/a000334. https://doi.org/10.1027/1864-1105/a000334
differences: One item was changed in wording ("Based on feedback from the pretest, minor linguistic adjustments were made (e.g., “. . . I manage to distance myself from my (work) tasks” instead of “. . . dis- tance myself from work”) to ensure that non-working individuals also feel addressed.) The SEM that we fitted did not exactly represent the one in original study. In the original study several items were deleted to achieve good model fit. However, this procedure was not outlined in the paper, and we could not get the exact model from the original authors. In the original study, participants were collected via the sosci panel and additionally via Facebook. In the replication, participants were collected via Facebook.

tags: time, money, scarcity, time-money tradeoffs, wage rates, procedural invariance
description: By manipulating the timing of an activity, the Time-Elicit (TEL) procedure of stating the maximum amount of hours required for a task should be more sensitive to a change in time scarcity, because time of money required for a task). Analogously, the TEL procedure should be more sensitive to a change in the timing of the activity. That is, distant activitiesscarcity receives a higher weight in TEL vs. Money-Elicit (MEL) procedure - stating the minimum amount should yield lower wage rates, particularly in the TEL (vs. MEL) procedure, which should diminish the wage rate asymmetry

tags: Freezing response to social threat
description: Freezing is an adaptive defensive response to a stressful event. It is characterized by reduced body motion, reduced heart rate (bradycardia), and increased muscle tonus. Social threats in the context of these studies are stimuli of angry faces.
notes: "To conclude, the current research has largely replicated the freezing-to-social-threat effect initially demonstrated by Roelofs et al. (2010). We hope our work strengthens the confidence in the effect and paves the way for further research and applications in the context of (social) threat and physiology", but in a personal correspondence, Hilbert wrote that the results were ambiguous, thats why we decided to label it as an inconclusive result
notes_validation: Among the effects reported in the original paper, only the effect on heart rate slowing (bradycardia) was tested in the replication study.
ref_original: Roelofs, K., Hagenaars, M. A., & Stins, J. (2010). Facing freeze: Social threat induces bodily freeze in humans. Psychological Science, 21, 1575–1581. https://doi.org/10.1177/0956797610384746
refonly_original: Roelofs, K., Hagenaars, M. A., & Stins, J. (2010). Facing freeze: Social threat induces bodily freeze in humans. Psychological Science, 21, 1575–1581. https://doi.org/10.1177/0956797610384746
ref_replication: Noordewier, M. K., Scheepers, D. T., & Hilbert, L. P. (2020). Freezing in response to social threat: a replication. Psychological Research, 84, 1890-1896. https://doi.org/10.1007/s00426-019-01203-4
refonly_replication: Noordewier, M. K., Scheepers, D. T., & Hilbert, L. P. (2020). Freezing in response to social threat: a replication. Psychological Research, 84, 1890-1896. https://doi.org/10.1007/s00426-019-01203-4

tags: self-concept clarity, subscription services, self-signaling, retention choice, self-concept structure, identity signaling
description: If you are uncertain about your own self-concept, then you will not want to introduce even more uncertainty by altering your identity. Consumers with “low self-concept clarity” should therefore be more motivated to keep their identities stable by (1) retaining products that are relevant to their identities, and (2) choosing not to acquire new products that are relevant to their identities.
notes_validation: Retention condition

I used the corrected correlations. Because: "Specifically, we used the  Spearman-Brown prediction formula and Spearman disattenuation formula to estimate the trait–outcome associations that would be expected if our outcome measure had used the same number of items or indicators 
as in the original study (Lord & Novick, 1968). These corrected associations address the possibility that some failures to replicate could simply reflect the attenuated reliability and validity of the abbreviated measures." (Soto, 2019).  All effect sizes are oriented so that positive values represent 
effects in the hypothesized direction.

refonly_original: Makhanova, A., Miller, S. L., & Maner, J. K. (2015). Germs and the out-group: Chronic and situational disease concerns affect intergroup categorization. Evolutionary Behavioral Sciences, 9(1), 8–19.
ref_replication: Makhanova, A., Eubanks, A. D., & Maner, J. K. (2023). Does pathogen avoidance affect intergroup categorization? Replication of Makhanova, Miller, and Maner (2015). Evolutionary Behavioral Sciences, 17(2), 171–186.
refonly_replication: Makhanova, A., Eubanks, A. D., & Maner, J. K. (2023). Does pathogen avoidance affect intergroup categorization? Replication of Makhanova, Miller, and Maner (2015). Evolutionary Behavioral Sciences, 17(2), 171–186. https://doi.org/10.1037/ebs0000279
p_es_orig:
Sample size original study: Method section, Participants sub-section, p 14
 Test statistic and partial eta squared from original study: Result section, end of first paragraph, p 14
 
 Sample size replicated study: p. 175, Method section, Participants sub-section
 Test statistic and partial eta squared from original study: p. 176, Results section, Replication analyses sub-section, end of first paragraph
 
 These results are for their three-way interaction between target type, germ aversion, and priming condition.
differences: Original study used a news article about the H1N1 influence virus to experimentally increase pathogen avoidance , whereas the replication study used an article about the Covid-19 virus

description: Priming analytic thinking using the scrambled sentence task reduces belief in conspiracy theories
ref_original: Swami, V., Voracek, M., Stieger, S., Tran, U. S., & Furnham, A. (2014). Analytic thinking reduces belief in conspiracy theories. Cognition, 133 (3), 572–585. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cognition.2014.08.006, Study 2
refonly_original: Swami, V., Voracek, M., Stieger, S., Tran, U. S., & Furnham, A. (2014). Analytic thinking reduces belief in conspiracy theories. Cognition, 133 (3), 572–585. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cognition.2014.08.006
ref_replication: Većkalov, B., Gligorić, V., & Petrović, M. B. (2024). No evidence that priming analytic thinking reduces belief in conspiracy theories: A Registered Report of high-powered direct replications of Study 2 and Study 4 from Swami, Voracek, Stieger, Tran, and Furnham (2014). Journal of Experimental Social Psychology,Vol. 110, 104549. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jesp.2023.104549, Study 1
refonly_replication: Većkalov, B., Gligorić, V., & Petrović, M. B. (2024). No evidence that priming analytic thinking reduces belief in conspiracy theories: A Registered Report of high-powered direct replications of Study 2 and Study 4 from Swami, Voracek, Stieger, Tran, and Furnham (2014). Journal of Experimental Social Psychology,Vol. 110, 104549. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jesp.2023.104549
p_es_orig:
Swami et al (2014) page 578
 Veckalov et al (2024) page 4.
 
 NB. Both studie were ANOVAs so several test statistics were reported. However, given that this is a ranomised experiment with a treatment condition and a control condition I decided that the most appopriate statistical test to report is the t-test comparing the two groups after the treatment has been applied.
differences:
Original was lab-based and recurited UK undergrad students. Replication was online and recurited from a UK pool. 
 
 Original doesn't appear to involve any remuneration (although this isn't specificaly stated). Replicatication involved payment.
 
 Original doesn't appear to have any participant exclusions (although this isn't specifically stated). Replication excluded participants who failed quality checks.

differences:
Original was in person and recruited participants from the community in London, UK.
 Replication was online and recurited from a UK pool.
 
 Original paid participants £1.50. Replicatication paid participants, but it isn't clear how much.
 
 Original doesn't appear to have any participant exclusions (although this isn't specifically stated). Replication excluded participants who failed quality checks.
